05797nam a22008175i 9781479828210DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798282107 a10.18574/nyu/9781479844630.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548134  a(OCoLC)1004612401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0130002bisacsh04a305.80097300aRacial Reconciliation and the Healing of a Nation :bBeyond Law and Rights /ced. by Charles J. Ogletree Jr., Austin Sarat. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Charles Hamilton Houston Institute Series on Race and Justice ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Bridging the Black- White Divide -- t1. Racial fakery and the next postracial: Reconciliation in the Age of Dolezal -- t2. Race and science: Preconciliation as reconciliation -- t3. From perceiving injustice to achieving racial justice: interrogating the impact of racial brokers on racial antagonism and racial reconciliation -- t4. Weaponized empathy: emotion and the limits of racial reconciliation in policing -- t5. Black deaths matter, too: doing racial reconciliation after the massacre at Emanuel Ame church in Charleston, south Carolina -- t6. The “post- national” racial state, domestication, and multiscalar organizing in the new millennium -- tAbout the editors -- tAbout the contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe work at hand for bridging the racial divide in the United States From Baltimore and Ferguson to Flint and Charleston, the dream of a post-racial era in America has run up against the continuing reality of racial antagonism. Current debates about affirmative action, multiculturalism, and racial hate speech reveal persistent uncertainty and ambivalence about the place and meaning of race – and especially the black/white divide – in American culture. They also suggest that the work of racial reconciliation remains incomplete. Racial Reconciliation and the Healing of a Nation seeks to assess where we are in that work, examining sources of continuing racial antagonism among blacks and whites. It also highlights strategies that promise to promote racial reconciliation in the future. Rather than revisit arguments about the importance of integration, assimilation, and reparations, the contributors explore previously unconsidered perspectives on reconciliation between blacks and whites. Chapters connect identity politics, the rhetoric of race and difference, the work of institutions and actors in those institutions, and structural inequities in the lives of blacks and whites to our thinking about tolerance and respect. Going beyond an assessment of the capacity of law to facilitate racial reconciliation, Racial Reconciliation and the Healing of a Nation challenges readers to examine social, political, cultural, and psychological issues that fuel racial antagonism, as well as the factors that might facilitate racial reconciliation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aRace discrimination--United States. 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bisacsh1 aCooper, Valerie C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorr, Kirstie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurakawa, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aObasogie, Osagie K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgletree Jr., Charles J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOgletree, Charles J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt Guterl, Matthew, econtr